{
  "The Mid-Atlantic Ridge is an example of what type of geological feature?": "",
  "A mid-ocean ridge at a divergent plate boundary": "",
  "A subduction zone trench": "",
  "A transform fault": "",
  "A hotspot volcanic chain": "",
  "The Mid-Atlantic Ridge is the longest mountain range on Earth, running approximately 16,000 km through the center of the Atlantic Ocean. It is a divergent plate boundary where the North American and Eurasian plates (and the South American and African plates) are moving apart.": "",
  "Which ocean trench is the deepest point on Earth?": "",
  "Mariana Trench": "",
  "Java Trench": "",
  "Puerto Rico Trench": "",
  "Tonga Trench": "",
  "The Mariana Trench in the western Pacific Ocean contains the Challenger Deep, the deepest known point on Earth at approximately 10,994 meters (36,070 feet) below sea level. It was formed by the subduction of the Pacific Plate beneath the Mariana Plate.": "",
  "What type of volcanic activity occurs at mid-ocean ridges?": "",
  "No volcanic activity occurs at ridges": "",
  "Eruptions of ash and pyroclastic flows only": "",
  "Explosive eruptions of thick, silica-rich lava": "",
  "Effusive eruptions of thin, basaltic lava": "",
  "Mid-ocean ridge volcanism is characterized by effusive (non-explosive) eruptions of basaltic lava with low silica content. The lava flows out gently, often forming pillow basalt structures when it comes into contact with cold seawater and cools rapidly.": "",
  "What is the Ring of Fire?": "",
  "A zone of hydrothermal vents in the Arctic Ocean": "",
  "A chain of mid-ocean ridges encircling the Atlantic Ocean": "",
  "A series of hotspot volcanoes in the Indian Ocean": "",
  "A belt of volcanic and seismic activity surrounding the Pacific Ocean": "",
  "The Ring of Fire is a horseshoe-shaped zone of intense volcanic and earthquake activity that encircles the Pacific Ocean. It is home to about 75% of the world's active volcanoes and approximately 90% of the world's earthquakes, caused by the numerous subduction zones along its path.": "",
  "How do ocean trenches form?": "",
  "Sediment accumulation creates deep valleys": "",
  "One tectonic plate is forced beneath another at a subduction zone": "",
  "Erosion by deep-sea currents carves out depressions": "",
  "Magma withdrawal leaves empty chambers that collapse": "",
  "Ocean trenches form at convergent plate boundaries where one plate subducts (dives beneath) another. The downward bending of the subducting plate creates a long, narrow, and extremely deep depression on the ocean floor, known as a trench.": "",
  "The East Pacific Rise is known for having:": "",
  "The slowest spreading rate of any mid-ocean ridge": "",
  "One of the fastest spreading rates of any mid-ocean ridge": "",
  "The deepest rift valley of any ridge system": "",
  "No volcanic activity": "",
  "The East Pacific Rise has one of the fastest spreading rates among mid-ocean ridges, with some sections spreading at rates up to 15 cm per year. Fast-spreading ridges tend to have broader, gentler profiles and shallower or absent rift valleys compared to slow-spreading ridges.": "",
  "What is a rift valley at a mid-ocean ridge?": "",
  "A central depression along the crest of the ridge where plates pull apart": "",
  "A deep trench caused by subduction": "",
  "A canyon on the continental shelf": "",
  "A flat area between two seamounts": "",
  "A rift valley is the depression that runs along the central axis of a mid-ocean ridge. It forms where tectonic plates are actively pulling apart, and is the site where magma rises and new oceanic crust is generated. Slow-spreading ridges tend to have more prominent rift valleys.": "",
  "What are black smokers?": "",
  "Dark-colored seamounts near ocean trenches": "",
  "Undersea mud volcanoes on the continental slope": "",
  "Volcanic vents on mid-ocean ridges that emit dark, mineral-rich superheated water": "",
  "Deep ocean currents that carry black sediment": "",
  "Black smokers are hydrothermal vents found along mid-ocean ridges that emit superheated water (up to 400°C) rich in dissolved minerals. The 'smoke' is actually a cloud of dark metal sulfide particles that precipitate when the hot fluid meets cold seawater.": "",
  "An island arc forms when:": "",
  "Sediment from turbidity currents builds islands on the abyssal plain": "",
  "A hotspot creates a chain of volcanoes as a plate moves over it": "",
  "Coral reefs build up around a sinking volcanic island": "",
  "One oceanic plate subducts beneath another, producing a curved chain of volcanic islands": "",
  "Island arcs form at convergent boundaries where one oceanic plate subducts beneath another. The subducting plate melts in the mantle, and the resulting magma rises to the surface, creating a curved chain of volcanic islands parallel to the trench. Examples include the Aleutian Islands and the Mariana Islands.": "",
  "Approximately what percentage of Earth's volcanic activity occurs along mid-ocean ridges?": "",
  "About 50%": "",
  "About 75%": "",
  "About 10%": "",
  "About 25%": "",
  "Approximately 75% of Earth's volcanic activity occurs along mid-ocean ridges, most of it underwater and unobserved. This volcanism is responsible for creating all new oceanic crust through the process of seafloor spreading, making ridges the most volcanically active features on Earth.": "",
  "What is the definition of a 'mid-ocean ridge'?": "",
  "A deep depression in the center of an ocean basin": "",
  "A continuous underwater mountain system formed at divergent plate boundaries": "",
  "A chain of volcanic islands formed over a hotspot": "",
  "A flat-topped seamount in the middle of the ocean": "",
  "A mid-ocean ridge is a continuous chain of underwater mountains that forms along divergent plate boundaries where tectonic plates are spreading apart. The global mid-ocean ridge system is the longest mountain range on Earth, extending over 65,000 km through all major ocean basins.": "",
  "What is a 'trench' in marine geology?": "",
  "A shallow depression on the continental shelf": "",
  "A long, narrow, deep depression in the ocean floor formed at a subduction zone": "",
  "A groove along the center of a mid-ocean ridge": "",
  "A canyon carved by river flow on the ocean floor": "",
  "An ocean trench is a long, narrow, and very deep depression in the ocean floor that forms at subduction zones where one tectonic plate descends beneath another. Trenches are the deepest features on Earth's surface, with depths exceeding 6,000 meters and sometimes reaching nearly 11,000 meters.": "",
  "The term 'pillow basalt' refers to:": "",
  "Basalt that forms columnar joints on land": "",
  "Rounded, pillow-shaped formations of basaltic lava that cooled rapidly underwater": "",
  "Basalt eroded into smooth shapes by ocean currents": "",
  "Soft sediment found near hydrothermal vents": "",
  "Pillow basalts are rounded, pillow-shaped formations of basaltic lava created when hot lava erupts underwater and the outer surface quickly cools and solidifies upon contact with cold seawater. They are characteristic of mid-ocean ridge eruptions and are commonly found on the seafloor.": "",
  "What is a 'fracture zone' on the ocean floor?": "",
  "A zone of volcanic eruptions at a hotspot": "",
  "A linear zone of irregular topography that offsets a mid-ocean ridge, associated with transform faults": "",
  "A region of the continental shelf prone to earthquakes": "",
  "An area of deep-sea sediment that has been fractured by pressure": "",
  "Fracture zones are linear features on the ocean floor that offset segments of mid-ocean ridges. They are associated with transform faults, where ridge segments are displaced horizontally. Fracture zones extend beyond the active fault as inactive scars on the ocean floor.": "",
  "What does the term 'spreading rate' mean in the context of mid-ocean ridges?": "",
  "The rate at which sediment accumulates on the ridge": "",
  "The speed at which lava flows along the ridge crest": "",
  "The rate at which tectonic plates move apart at a divergent boundary": "",
  "The rate at which the ridge erodes over time": "",
  "The spreading rate is the velocity at which two tectonic plates move apart at a mid-ocean ridge, typically measured in centimeters per year. Spreading rates vary from slow (1–5 cm/yr, like the Mid-Atlantic Ridge) to fast (6–16 cm/yr, like the East Pacific Rise).": "",
  "What is an 'island arc'?": "",
  "A row of flat-topped guyots along a ridge": "",
  "A curved chain of volcanic islands formed above a subduction zone": "",
  "A series of barrier islands along a continental coast": "",
  "A group of coral atolls in the tropics": "",
  "An island arc is a chain of volcanic islands arranged in a curved (arcuate) shape, formed at a convergent boundary where one oceanic plate subducts beneath another. The arc shape results from the geometry of subduction on a spherical Earth. Examples include Japan, the Philippines, and the Aleutian Islands.": "",
  "The term 'Wadati-Benioff zone' describes:": "",
  "The zone of volcanic activity along a mid-ocean ridge": "",
  "A planar zone of earthquakes that marks the position of a subducting plate": "",
  "The region between an island arc and a trench": "",
  "The area of deepest water in an ocean trench": "",
  "The Wadati-Benioff zone is an inclined plane of earthquake foci that dips from near the surface at an ocean trench to deep within the mantle beneath the overriding plate. It traces the path of the subducting plate and helps scientists determine the angle and depth of subduction.": "",
  "What is the 'Challenger Deep'?": "",
  "A volcanic caldera on the Mid-Atlantic Ridge": "",
  "A deep-water coral reef in the North Pacific": "",
  "A deep submarine canyon off the coast of South America": "",
  "The deepest known point in the ocean, located in the Mariana Trench": "",
  "The Challenger Deep is the deepest known point in Earth's oceans, reaching approximately 10,994 meters (about 36,070 feet) below sea level. Located in the southern end of the Mariana Trench in the western Pacific, it was named after the HMS Challenger II, which first surveyed its depth in 1951.": "",
  "The term 'back-arc basin' refers to:": "",
  "A basin formed behind a volcanic island arc due to extension of the overriding plate": "",
  "A sediment-filled depression on the continental shelf": "",
  "The area of ocean between two mid-ocean ridges": "",
  "The deepest part of an ocean trench": "",
  "A back-arc basin is a region of seafloor spreading and extension that forms behind (on the overriding plate side of) a volcanic island arc. Tensional forces caused by the subduction process can stretch and thin the overriding plate, creating a small basin with its own spreading center.": "",
  "What does the term 'accretionary wedge' mean?": "",
  "A deposit of coral and shell fragments on the continental shelf": "",
  "A pile of volcanic material built up at a mid-ocean ridge": "",
  "A formation of ice at the poles that pushes the seafloor down": "",
  "A wedge-shaped accumulation of sediment scraped off from a subducting plate at a trench": "",
  "An accretionary wedge (or accretionary prism) is a mass of sediment and rock scraped off the subducting oceanic plate as it descends beneath the overriding plate at a trench. These wedge-shaped accumulations grow over time and can form a ridge along the inner wall of the trench.": "",
  "Scientists compare the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, which spreads at about 2.5 cm/year, with the East Pacific Rise, which spreads at about 15 cm/year. How would you expect their cross-sectional profiles to differ?": "",
  "Both ridges would have identical profiles regardless of spreading rate": "",
  "The Mid-Atlantic Ridge would have a steep profile with a deep rift valley, while the East Pacific Rise would have a broad, gentle profile": "",
  "The Mid-Atlantic Ridge would be broader and gentler, while the East Pacific Rise would be steeper": "",
  "The East Pacific Rise would have a deeper rift valley than the Mid-Atlantic Ridge": "",
  "Slow-spreading ridges like the Mid-Atlantic Ridge have steep, rugged profiles with prominent central rift valleys because the crust has more time to cool and fracture. Fast-spreading ridges like the East Pacific Rise have broader, gentler profiles with shallow or absent rift valleys due to higher magma supply rates.": "",
  "The Mariana Trench reaches a depth of nearly 11,000 meters, while Mount Everest rises to about 8,849 meters. If you could place Mount Everest at the bottom of the Mariana Trench, what would happen?": "",
  "Mount Everest would be 5,000 meters below the surface": "",
  "The peak of Mount Everest would still be about 2,000 meters below the ocean surface": "",
  "Mount Everest would rise above sea level": "",
  "Mount Everest would exactly reach sea level": "",
  "The Mariana Trench is approximately 10,994 m deep and Mount Everest is 8,849 m tall. Placing Everest at the bottom would leave its peak at roughly 10,994 − 8,849 ≈ 2,145 m below sea level. This illustrates the extraordinary depth of ocean trenches compared to the tallest feature on land.": "",
  "A volcanologist studying an island in the Ring of Fire observes explosive eruptions producing andesitic lava with high silica content. This volcanic activity is most likely caused by:": "",
  "A hotspot mantle plume": "",
  "A mid-ocean ridge underneath the island": "",
  "Transform faulting between two oceanic plates": "",
  "Subduction of an oceanic plate, with meltwater and sediment mixing into magma": "",
  "Explosive volcanism with andesitic (intermediate silica content) lava is characteristic of subduction zone volcanoes. Water carried down by the subducting plate lowers the melting point of mantle rock, and the resulting magma mixes with silica-rich sediments, producing more viscous, explosive eruptions.": "",
  "Iceland sits directly on a mid-ocean ridge. What unique geological situation makes Iceland visible above sea level?": "",
  "Iceland is a continental fragment, not oceanic crust": "",
  "Sea level has dropped enough to expose the ridge at Iceland": "",
  "Iceland is on a convergent boundary, building mountains above the surface": "",
  "Iceland has extra volcanic output because it sits on both a mid-ocean ridge and a mantle hotspot": "",
  "Iceland is one of the few places on Earth where a mid-ocean ridge is visible above sea level. This is because the island sits at the junction of the Mid-Atlantic Ridge and a deep mantle hotspot, which provides an unusually large volume of magma that builds the island above the ocean surface.": "",
  "Seismic data from a region near an ocean trench shows shallow earthquakes near the trench surface, intermediate-depth earthquakes farther inland, and deep earthquakes deepest beneath the overriding plate. What pattern does this describe?": "",
  "Normal faulting at a divergent boundary": "",
  "A hotspot plume rising through the mantle": "",
  "A transform fault system with variable depths": "",
  "A Wadati-Benioff zone showing the angle of the subducting plate": "",
  "The pattern of earthquakes increasing in depth from the trench surface toward the overriding plate defines the Wadati-Benioff zone. This inclined plane of seismicity traces the upper surface of the subducting plate as it descends into the mantle, allowing scientists to determine subduction angle and depth.": "",
  "A marine geologist compares sediment cores from the inner wall of an ocean trench and finds layers of crumpled, deformed rock mixed with ocean floor sediment. What feature is this sediment part of?": "",
  "A turbidite fan": "",
  "An accretionary wedge": "",
  "A coral reef formation": "",
  "A mid-ocean ridge basalt layer": "",
  "Crumpled, deformed rock and scraped-off ocean floor sediment on the inner wall of a trench are characteristic of an accretionary wedge. As the subducting plate descends, sediment and rock are scraped off and piled up against the overriding plate, forming this compressional feature.": "",
  "Researchers discover thriving communities of tube worms and other organisms near black smokers along a mid-ocean ridge in the deep ocean where no sunlight reaches. These organisms most likely depend on:": "",
  "Organic matter sinking from the surface (marine snow)": "",
  "Geothermal energy directly absorbed by their tissues": "",
  "Photosynthesis using bioluminescent light": "",
  "Chemosynthesis by bacteria that obtain energy from chemicals in vent fluids": "",
  "Deep-sea vent communities rely on chemosynthetic bacteria that convert chemicals like hydrogen sulfide from hydrothermal fluids into energy. These bacteria form the base of the food web, supporting tube worms, clams, and other organisms in complete darkness without any dependence on sunlight.": "",
  "A mapping expedition finds that the ocean floor on one side of a mid-ocean ridge is 5 million years old at a distance of 50 km from the ridge axis. What is the half-spreading rate?": "",
  "10 cm/year": "",
  "5 cm/year": "",
  "2 cm/year": "",
  "1 cm/year": "",
  "Half-spreading rate = distance / time = 50 km / 5 million years = 10 km/million years = 1 cm/year. The half-spreading rate measures how fast one plate moves away from the ridge axis. The full spreading rate (both plates combined) would be 2 cm/year.": "",
  "A government agency is evaluating tsunami risk for a coastal city. They know the city faces an ocean with a subduction zone trench 500 km offshore. A scientist explains that the trench poses a significant tsunami risk. Why?": "",
  "Trenches focus wave energy toward the coast": "",
  "Subduction zone earthquakes can vertically displace large volumes of water, generating tsunamis": "",
  "The trench blocks normal ocean currents, causing dangerous wave buildup": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions in the trench create large waves reaching the coast": "",
  "Subduction zones generate the most powerful earthquakes on Earth, and when these quakes cause sudden vertical displacement of the ocean floor, enormous volumes of water are displaced, creating tsunamis. The 2004 Indian Ocean and 2011 Japan tsunamis were both caused by subduction zone earthquakes.": "",
  "A deep-sea exploration vehicle descends into an ocean trench and records water temperatures just above freezing (1–4°C) and extreme pressures exceeding 1,000 atmospheres. Despite these conditions, the vehicle's cameras record living organisms on the trench floor. What adaptations would these organisms most likely need?": "",
  "Hard exoskeletons to resist pressure and ability to photosynthesize using geothermal light": "",
  "Flexible cell membranes to resist crushing pressure and specialized enzymes that function at low temperatures": "",
  "Large eyes to see in the dark and warm-blooded metabolism for the cold": "",
  "Photosynthetic pigments for energy and thick shells for insulation": "",
  "Organisms in deep ocean trenches (hadal zone) require specialized adaptations including flexible, unsaturated cell membranes that remain functional under extreme pressure, and cold-adapted enzymes (psychrophilic proteins) that work efficiently at near-freezing temperatures. Many also have slow metabolisms to conserve energy.": ""
}